This is rifle is a beast. It has the AK style upper with a AR lower. It has a left sided bolt on it, for tactical reloading. Folding stock w/ a 16" heavy barrel.

Flip up sights

postcontent:
This gun is extremely hard to find with just the standard sights, and nearly impossible with the quick sights. This one has Waffen Werks import marks.

It is in mint condition with about 300 rounds down the barrel.

The Quick Acquisition Sights (QAS) put both the rear and front sight on the same focal plane so you can acquire targets incredibly fast.

The gun has one of the lowest bore axis in it's class, reducing recoil dramatically.

Trigger is one of the smoothest DA triggers on the market. I've heard it compared to a Walther PPQ.

Comes with the case and manual, lock, and 2 mags. May also come with a Blackhawk nylon IWB holster and a molded OWB leather holster.

I'm not desperate to sell or trade this gun at all. Also not looking to add any cash.

Note: There IS a voluntary recall out on this gun. If you wish to send the gun in, Caracal will replace the gun with a brand new one along with a free mag, shirt, hat, and 15% off coupon.

CONDITION: THIS GUN IS COMPLETELY DISASSEMBLED.

It was inherited in this condition from a relative's estate in 2004.

Unfired by me, history earlier than 2004 unknown.

3-digit Serial Number (7xx, no prefix) located on Receiver and Buttstock dates this as manufactured in 1939.

The Official Gun Digest Book of Guns & Prices, 2007:
"The Model 39A Lever-Action Rifle is an improved version of the Model 39. It has a heavier, tapered round barrel, semi-beavertail forearm and a redesigned pistol-grip stock. The Model 39's rubber buttplate was replaced by one made of synthetic fiber; otherwise, specifications were similar to the Model 39. The Model 39A was manufactured from 1939 to 1960. Pre-war variations (1939-1941): case-colored receiver with no serial number prefix (1939), or "B" prefix (1940-1941)."

.22 S/L/LR Lever-Action . . . 24-in. Round Barrel . . . Black Walnut Buttstock & Forearm, finish removed from Buttstock.

Case Hardened Receiver, Lever and Trigger. Some rust on the Barrel and Magazine Tube, but someone who knows what they're doing could clean it up and have a nice vintage 39A.

title: For Sale:  Bulgarian Arsenal SLR-101S AK-47 Milled Receiver
postcontent:
Merry Christmas to you from you.  Best of the best.  If you know what it is you're interested.  If you don't and you want an AK be sure to read below.  These don't come available very often.  It is in like new condition. 

I am selling an as new Bulgarian made Arsenal SLR-101S AK rifle, caliber 7.62x39mm. The SLR101 is made in Bulgaria and imported as a complete rifle. This means both the receiver and barrel are original Arsenal BG milspec. Rifle comes with 1 Bulgarian made 40rd. magazine and sling. The original Soviet Russian AK47 utilized a milled receiver from the late 1940s until the adoption of the less expensive and lighter AKM in 1959. Most other Warsaw Pact nations followed suit and switched from the milled AK47 to the stamped AKM. While Arsenal in Bulgaria did manufacture stamped rifles starting in the 1960s, it never abandoned the milled design and continued to update and modernize it. The Bulgarian military has been using these weapons for decades, in various configurations.
Back in 2001, Arsenal Inc. of NV in the USA imported a milled rifle from Arsenal of Bulgaria called the SLR101. This rifle had an original Bulgarian made milled receiver, as well as an original Bulgarian barrel. This line was discontinued 10 years ago and only in 2012 has Arsenal once again imported a batch of SLR101s. Arsenal has done the SA M7 line with a milled receiver, but with one key difference; the SA M series used a US made milled receiver and other US parts. The SLR101 is wholly made in Bulgaria and is imported into the US as a complete weapon. It is brought in without a bayonet lug and with a thumbhole stock, to get around import restrictions. Once in the country, Arsenal Inc. installs a proper butt stock, pistol grip, and muzzle brake. They also insure the rifle is capable of accepting any standard AK double stack, high capacity magazines. All parts are Bulgarian made, except for the required 922(r) ones. These parts are made in the USA by Arsenal, but to original Bulgarian specifications and include: the furniture set, trigger group, and muzzle brake.
Comparing the 2012 SLR101-13 to the 2001 SLR101s, the same manufacturing quality and fit and finish can be found. Since the 2001 rifles were sold during the 1994 Clinton AWB, they were not allowed to have either the removable muzzle device, threaded barrel, or bayonet lug. These modern SLR101 rifles though have all of these features as the AWB sunset in 2004.
This rifle features: original Arsenal of Bulgaria AK47 style milled receiver, original 16" long Cold Hammer Forged barrel with a chrome lined bore, standard 14mm threads on the end of the barrel, side-mount on the receiver for optics, a smooth double hook trigger, intermediate length polymer butt stock, milspec polymer hand guards with steel heat shield, standard military pistol grip, and the ability to accept any standard AK47/AKM magazines and drums. These milled Arsenals are known for their reliability and trouble-free service; but if it does have any problems, it is fully covered under Arsenal's warranty. It has been a decade since any milled receiver rifles have come in from Bulgaria and I don't think I am out of line in saying they are some of the finest AK pattern rifles ever produced. All moving parts work smoothly; the rifle is very accurate, durable, and great looking.
